"In this world where you can be anything be kind."
~Unknown

A kind gesture.
A kind word
A kind heart
Are underrated.

It is so easy to take things for granted when we are moving through life at a lightning-speed pace. We can easily forget to slow down and be kind. Being kind verbally and physically... 
Treat someone to their favorite movie/meal/drink, ask if they need assistance, donate your time or money, lend your belongings, let the other driver pass when you're on the road, speak in a kind tone and words, listen more, and set an example are some ways you can be kind. You don't know how this can change someone's day. Show concern for the feelings of others and be kind.

😍😮You know… I read things quickly and as I have time on here… because of my “PTSD” apparently now I take it 1 day at a time to even bring back the “Fire” I’ve dreamt of for my business…funny how I read or I should say listened to a book about it right when it happened to me… a fall that will leave nightmares forever.. but I can’t keep letting it bring me down I have to stop and think and try to get more help from doctors to better understand the “Crazy Things” in my head these days. Depression is the worst part of it which helped me better understand the ones I Love Most! So on that I’m going to go back to relying on “Faith in God” and Faith in what god has planned for my future… because I have certain few that have stood beside me no matter what I’ve suffered and those are the ones that understand me and the ones that truly love me… I have no ill will towards anyone what I do want is to feel safe again and know that I can trust the one by my side for LIFE! And to make sure I give the same 💙💙💙 until you suffer this you will never understand Be Blessed and never take for granted the ones that stand beside you no matter what

laurencebailliebrown Last Sunday we celebrated, with
family and friends, music and afternoon tea, a Double
Book Launch. This is a new edition of my first novel in
which 2 themes intertwine. In witty, bitchy letters
passing between London and San Diego, 2 mature
gay men, intimate friends, discuss their adventures
and desires. It is 1990 and back home, Margaret
Thatcher's power begins to totter. Interwoven
between the letters are autobiographical sketches,
written by a younger musician who writes about
growing up Jewish and gay in the North of England in
the mid-20th century. "We could read this as a
picaresque story of sexual encounters, the way desire
brings people together and flings them apart with
heart-breaking speed. But on closer reading it
becomes clear..the hero of the story is in fact the
'enduring love' of true friendship" Quoted from the
introduction by Professor Jane Spiro of Oxford
Brookes University.

laurencebailliebrown In witty, bitchy letters passing
between London and San Diego, two gay men who
are intinmate friends discuss their adventures and
desires. Jeremy, an opera conductor, and Francis, a
visiting professor of literature in California, conduct
their intrigues over the course of 1990-91. Interwoven
between the letters are autobiographical sketches,
written by Jonathan, a protege of Jeremy's, who
writes about growing up gay and Jewish in the North
of England and coming out in the more innocent
London of the late 70sand 80s.
"In the end it turns out all these characters have been
inhabiting a farce - and a Shakespearian one at that.
Delightful" said 'Gay Times'. And in her introduction to
this second edition, Professor Jane Spiro writes "We
could read this as a picaresque story of 
encounters, the way desire brings people together
and flings them apart with heartbreaking speed. But
on closer reading it becomes clear...the hero of the
story is in fact the 'enduring love' of true friendship."
Why not see if you agree with them? And there's a
sequel -'97 or and Sensibility' to come shortly.
Enjoy!
